(240683, 8057, 0, 'BaderJanjua', 133, 'The birth of .45 calibre !', 1327038317, 'When Americans were fighting in Phillipines in the second decade of the 20th Century it was revealed to them that at close quarters their .38 revolvers which at that point of time were Colt 38 did little to stop well determined charging Mooro warriors especiall in thick growth. Thus was born the .45. During 2nd World War tha american side Arm was Colt 1911 while the Germans carried Luger and mauser Pistols in 9 mm. It was quoted that often during close battles inside trenches the shots by Germans would end up sending the American Soldiers to field Hospitals from where a good number would recover to once again join the battle lines while the shots taken by Americans equipped with Colt 45s would just slump the Germans dead in tracks. The 1911 .45 pistols became so popular with the soldiers that they preffered to use them instead of baynots . 8 rounds of .45 at close ranges with greater maneauverability would add a tremendous punch. However this did not mean that 9 mm lost its credibility, since it is still a very favourite cal and the development of ammo like Hydra Shock and other hollowpoints for Sd purposes may set aside the former reasoning. IMHO as it is said in most law enforcement and military circles that in combat pistols should help you to get to your rifles/shotguns or at the end are good for suicide as a last resort in heavy engagement.', 1, 0, '39.45.55.85', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 0, 0),
