(240953, 7675, 228480, 'HasanJamshad', 573, '', 1327139689, 'Avais bhai interesting question. I wasn''t aware of the answer so couldn''t stand the curiosity. Did some research and was even more confused. As it seems almost customary for the Remington to use abbreviations for defining a certain model like.\n1 700 SPS (Special Purpose Synthetic)\n2 700 XHR ( Xtreme Hunter Rifle)\n3 700 VLS  ( Varmint Laminated Stock)\n4 700 SPS DM (Special Purpose Synthetic Detachble Magazine)\n5 700 XCR (Xtreme Corrosion Resistant)\n6 700 VL SS (Varmint Laminated Stainless Steel)\n7 700 VTR (Varmint Tactical Rifle)\n8 700P (Police)\n9 700P TWS (Police Tactical Weapon System)\n\nUnfortunately the only un explainable abbreviations were ADL, BDL, and CDL. But how could it be possible??? I tried to dug further deep and came up with this information. \n\nInitially company introduced two models of 700, ADL and BDL. Remington 700 ADL was a low priced model having average finish and blind magazine. Remington 700 BDL was bit expensive and had better finish, black fore-end cap, hinged magazine floor-plate and pistol grip cap etc. Company was advertising these models in early seventies as "Deluxe" for ADL and "Custom Deluxe" for BDL (Ref "Field and Stream Jul 1974, Popular Science Sep 1971, Popular Mechanics Nov 1972" Basic difference between the two was hinged floor plate other than cosmetics. Here we may safely conclude that DL was for DELUXE and other abbreviations "A,B" were for distinguishing between the models without representing any specific word.\n\nFinally the last CDL. It is defined as in "Hunter''s Guide to Whitetail Rifles Pg 89" Classic Deluxe for more traditional looks, having oil finished walnut stock and satin blued barrel and action.', 1, 1, '139.190.99.103', 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'on_nl2br', 0, 0),
